narratives.question_text: What knowledge, skills, and insights did you develop by taking this course?
comments: By taking this course, I applied all of my previous knowledge from calc I and II to three dimensions. Integrating in 3 dimensions, line integrals, Stoke's Theorem, Green's Theorem, etc. We learned what dot-product and cross-product are. We applied the knowledge gained to find flux, work done, force, mass of an object, volume, area, etc.
Great overall knowledge about multivariable calculus

So many math skills. I learnt how to do triple integrals, find volumes of very complex figures, use differnt kind of multipliers, and complex derivatives. In general, I haven't learnt as much in any of my other classes before.
Vectors, triple integrals, type I and type II integrals, greens theorem, stokes theorem, change of variables, jacobians
Learned how to do multivariable calculus. A very useful and fun course.

narratives.question_text: What are the strengths and weaknesses of this course and how could it be improved?
comments:
Strength: Professor Smooke releases all the upcoming homework problem numbers for the rest of the summer on the first they of the course, so students who want to work at a faster pace, can work on their homework way before it is due.

The slides are also immediately released on the first day of the course, and all of them have pre-recorded videos. On the day of the class, Dr. Smooke would go over the material, which was really helpful. We would ask him the questions we had from the pre-recorded course or the current lecture, which made the course very interactive.  

Weakness: It is only a 5-week course. You have to be on top of your work every week. The material isn't very difficult, it's just you'd have to cover 8-13 chapters per week (due to the fact that the course is only 5 weeks)
Since the class was online and over the summer, it was super fast paced, and somewhat hard to follow, but Professor Smooke was a great professor and supported us along the way

Strengths: Prof. Smooke is amazing. He is just super nice, understanding, and always willing and available to meet one-on-one and expalin. He also tries to make the material fun. I liked taking it over the summer, because it finished quicker and the suffering was shorter. 
Weaknesses: the TA was very kind, but she didn't know much about the material and wasn't really good in explaining. I also wish we did not practise problems at class, but I think that because of the pressing schedule fo the summer session, we didin't have time.
Strengths were the fact that we had prerecorded lectures to watch and the live lectures were also recorded so we could go back and review.
Excellent prerecorded lectures and the professor engages with the students and material during the lectures.
I found the repeated lectures a bitt tedious but they also helped to grasp concepts since we were reviewing every class.

narratives.question_text: Would you recommend this course to another student? Please explain.
comments: Yes! If you have nothing else to do over the summer, definitely take it! If you have research or other obligations, think twice before enrolling in any course, just because the courses are very fast-paced.
Yes; take this over 120 if you like application-based problems more than theoretical

Yes, I would recommend this course if it is taught by Prof. Smooke to anyone who likes math. Despite the intense amount of homewrok (60 problems a week over the summer), I have never learnt so much and genuently enjoyed solving the problems. It looks mmuch more scary than it is. It was a great way to get done with that class before my sophomore year.
Yes! Taking this in the summer was super nice. I felt like I could really focus on the material and dig in and learn everything well.
